PLSC - Political Science Poli.Analysis & Data w/ Python¶

Summer 2023¶

Module 3¶

Pandas¶

Pandas stands for Python Data Analysis Library.

This library is the most important library for data analysis.

Mastering pandas is an important skill that you should have.

Once you learn pandas you will not need excel anymore!

pandas allows us to work with dataframes.

It is built for working structured and tabular data like excel or csv files.

Pandas is used in data science, machine learning, and business analytics for tasks such as data cleaning, data wrangling, exploratory data analysis (EDA), and data visualization.

Here are the things you could do with pandas¶

  • Data import export
  • Data Cleaning and Preprocessing
  • Data Aggregation and Grouping
  • Data Visualization

Best resource for mastering pandas is this book:¶

It is written by Pandas's creator, Wes McKinney.

You can access the book for free from this link.

Feel free to buy a paper copy if you want.

As always, look at the documentation from here for more information about what you can do with pandas.

Lastly, there has been recent development for data analysis using Python. Polars is a package built on top of pandas but faster than pandas. If you ever have very large datasets polars can handle much more quickly. But for now, I would recommend you to stick with pandas. Learn pandas first. More on polars, here.

Let's start!¶

Note that we cannot cover all the functions of pandas library.

I will mostly cover the most common and useful methods in pandas. To learn more, read the book, read the documentation, Youtube is also a great resource.

In [1]:
# to start using pandas, we have to first request pandas.
# Notice alias pd. We do not write pandas over and over again

import pandas as pd

Series¶

The first main data type we will learn about for pandas is the Series data type.

Very similar to a NumPy array.

Series can have axis labels such as variable names. Numpy array did not have that.

In [2]:
import numpy as np
In [3]:
# creating data

labels = ['a','b','c'] #list

my_list = [10,20,30] #list

arr = np.array([10,20,30]) #array

dictionary = {'a':10,'b':20,'c':30} #dictionary
In [4]:
# from list to series

pd.Series(data=my_list)
Out[4]:
0    10
1    20
2    30
dtype: int64
In [5]:
pd.Series(data=my_list,index=labels)
Out[5]:
a    10
b    20
c    30
dtype: int64
In [6]:
# from array to series

pd.Series(arr,labels)
Out[6]:
a    10
b    20
c    30
dtype: int64
In [7]:
# from dictonary

pd.Series(dictionary)
Out[7]:
a    10
b    20
c    30
dtype: int64

Index in pandas¶

The key to using a Series is understanding its index.

In [8]:
ser1 = pd.Series([1,2,3,4],index = ['USA', 'Germany','Mexico', 'S.Korea'])

ser1

dtype: int64

DataFrame¶

DataFrame is a excel-like tabular data structure.

It is combination of Series that share the same index.

Think of a database of students, their age, gender, school, gpa, major etc.

In [12]:

# We can also use from to import only a spesific method from a library

Mergeing¶

3 main ways of combining DataFrames together:

  • Merging
  • Joining
  • Concatenating
